               <head>The Funerary Papyrus of 'Enkhefenkhons.</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>Funerary text written for Ankhefenkhonsu, a priest ("god's father") of
                     the god Amonrasonther and "engraver of the House of Amun", preserving a text
                     combining elements from Book of the Dead, Book of the Hidden Chamber and the
                     Books of the Earth with many illustrations.</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="egy-Egy">Egyptian in Hierogplyphic script</textLang>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="scroll">
                     <supportDesc material="papyrus">
                        <support/>
                        <extent>A complete papyrus roll written along the fibres with the back being
                           blank. The papyrus is mounted on paper and housed in two glass cases.
                              <dimensions type="reconstructed" unit="mm">
                              <height>240</height>
                              <width>1250</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="frame" xml:id="frame1" unit="mm">
                              <height>240</height>
                              <width>645</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="frame" xml:id="frame2" unit="mm">
                              <height>240</height>
                              <width>605</width>
                        
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>Written in columns with an illustration between the units of texts
                           on the two outer parts of the complete papyrus roll.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>Likely written by one scribe, in black and red ink in "Book of the
                        Dead cursive".</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>Illustrations in three registers. Upper register: ba of the deceased
                        adoring Osiris, followed by groups of seated and standing hybrid deities;
                        number uncertain. Middle register: solar barque drawn through a serpent,
                        attended by deities with sceptres and life-symbols, with mummiform and
                        headless figures. Lower register: rebirth of the sun god emerging from the
                        serpent, accompanied by adoring deities and a winged serpent.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>


               </physDesc>


               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="-0980" notAfter="-0945">980-945
                        BC</origDate></origin>
                  <provenance>Possibly from <ref type="place_7001297">Thebes</ref>. Purchased by Colonel
                        Valentine Patrick Terrell Vivian in Egypt around 1882 and bequeathed to his
                        brother-in-law the Reverend Vivian Eccles Skrine. </provenance>
                  <acquisition>Given to the Bodleian by the Reverend Vivian Eccles Skrine
                     (1850-1925), 30 March 1913.</acquisition>
               </history>
